"{\"uid\": \"examiner.com.au-story-8730867-tasmanian-hero-ariarne-titmus-shines-at-paris-2024-olympics\", \"text\": \"It's fair to say Ariarne Titmus has made Australia proud, but she's made Tasmanian even prouder.  Loginor signup to continue reading  The Launceston-born swimmer returned from the 2024 Paris Olympics Games with two gold medals and two silver.  When Titmus won gold in the 2021 Tokyo Olympic Games, the whole of Sacred Heart Primary school watched her compete, and for good reason - because the Olympic champion was one of their own.  Titmus attended the school from kindergarten to grade six, and current principal Brent Wilson said she returned to her old stomping grounds shortly after the 2021 Olympics.  \\\"Ariarne visited the school, and we interviewed her. She gave up quite a bit of her time,\\\" Mr Wilson said.  \\\"She spent two or three hours signing autographs with the kids and doing all those good things.\\\"  Mr Wilson said Titmus had an \\\"absolutely sensational personality\\\", and she inspired the students.  \\\"She was really welcoming. She gave everybody the time they sought from her,\\\" he said.  \\\"We have a champions wall, and she signed that - the kids walked away knowing she's one of our girls.  \\\"We proudly put that on Facebook after she won her first gold in the Paris Olympics - her mum actually liked it.\\\"  Mr Wilson said Titmus was still the humble and friendly person she was as a student.  \\\"People tell me her personality has not changed; she was always friendly and well-liked by everyone,\\\" he said.  Growing up, Titmus swam with Riverside Swim Club and frequently attended the Launceston Aquatic Centre, where a pool was named after her.  Mr Wilson said Titmus was a shining example of believing in what you do and aiming for the stars.  \\\"The kids see her as one of us,\\\" he said.  \\\"If a student from Sacred Heart can achieve that, that's what they aspire to. Whether that's in swimming or something else.\\\"  Titmus 